{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015NrLtSxACtsf1SWsF7BGqz","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have enough context for a thorough review. Here are my findings:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Three Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll three changes are directionally correct and solve real problems. The `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern and the `--` hard filter are sound. The compound title guard in dedup is the most interesting change — it works for its stated purpose but has two edge cases worth considering. One consistency issue stands out: the `--` pattern should almost certainly also be in `METADATA_PATTERNS`, not only in `passesHardFilters`.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. The `--` filter is placed in the wrong layer and will miss the coalescing path\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:325`\n\nThe `--` check lives only in `passesHardFilters()`. However, `looksLikeMetadata()` is called in three additional places: the coalescing loop at lines 479 and 491, and the merge-block check at line 536. A `--VARIATION:` line sitting between two real title lines could still participate in coalescing because the coalescing guard checks `looksLikeMetadata()`, not `passesHardFilters()`.\n\nThe comment on the pattern says \"sub-section headers\" — that is exactly the same semantic category as `SEZON:`, `KATEGORIA:`, `PORCJI:` which all live in `METADATA_PATTERNS`. Placing `--` in `passesHardFilters` only gives partial protection.\n\n**Recommendation**: Add the pattern to `METADATA_PATTERNS` as well (or instead). It can stay in `passesHardFilters` too — the redundancy is harmless, and a comment like \"also in METADATA_PATTERNS\" makes the intent explicit:\n\n```typescript\n// METADATA_PATTERNS addition:\n/^--\\s*\\w/,    // \"--VARIATION:\", \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA\" sub-section headers\n\n// passesHardFilters can then either remove it (trusting looksLikeMetadata) or keep it with a note.\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 2. The compound guard `/ [+:] /` in dedup can over-protect noise survivors\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1195`\n\nThe guard fires on any title that contains a space-colon-space or space-plus-space. A candidate like `\"Ciasto: 200g mąki 3 jajka\"` contains ` : ` and would be protected from the shorter-wins rule even though it is clearly ingredient spillover. The `:` separator appears in structural section headers too (e.g., `\"MAIN RECIPE: Classic Tart\"`), though that particular case is already filtered earlier.\n\nThe pattern also does not cover ` & ` which line 348 treats as an equivalent multi-title separator — if `\"CIASTO & LODY\"` is a compound title and a shorter substring `\"CIASTO\"` is also a candidate, the guard would not protect it.\n\nThe risk is low in practice because hard filters and scoring should eliminate most noise before this point, but the guard is asymmetric with line 348's separator set (`[+:&/]`). At minimum, the inconsistency is a latent bug.\n\n**Recommendation**: Align the dedup guard with line 348's separator set for internal consistency:\n\n```typescript\nif (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n```\n\n(Omitting `/` is intentional — slash separators are breadcrumb-style and are filtered at line 321 when count >= 2, and a single-slash compound would be unusual in a dedup context.)\n\n### 3. `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern anchoring is correct but narrower than the real phenomenon\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:77`\n\n`/^MAIN\\s+RECIPE\\s*:/i` is anchored to the start of the string and requires `RECIPE` specifically. The stated motivation is \"structural prefix lines.\" Other structurally similar prefixes — `BASE RECIPE:`, `CLASSIC RECIPE:`, `ORIGINAL RECIPE:` — would not be caught. This is not wrong, but if the pattern was added to handle a real observed case, the comment should name the case. If it was added speculatively, it may not be needed.\n\nThis is not a bug, but if you start seeing `BASE RECIPE: ...` or similar survivors, the pattern will need expansion. Consider whether the existing colon-ending filter at line 330 (`/:\\s*$/.test(text.trim()) && !/ : /.test(text)`) would already catch `MAIN RECIPE: Classic Tart` (it would, since it ends with the value, not a bare colon). If the METADATA_PATTERNS entry is only needed to also suppress these in the coalescing path, that's the relevant distinction to document in the comment.\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n### The `/ [+:] /` test appears in three separate locations with slight variations\n\nLine 330 uses `/ : /`, line 348 uses `/ [+:&/] /`, and line 1195 uses `/ [+:] /`. All three encode the concept \"this is a compound separator, not a structural colon.\" The divergence between these three will become a maintenance problem when a new separator type is introduced. Consider extracting a shared constant or predicate:\n\n```typescript\nconst COMPOUND_SEPARATOR_RE = / [+:&] /;\n```\n\nand referencing it at all three sites.\n\n### The `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b` and `\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ` patterns in METADATA_PATTERNS have no line-start anchor\n\nThese are intentional (the comment explains OCR-corrupted prefixes). But they also mean a title like `\"STEK Z 30 MIN MARYNATY\"` (\"steak with 30-minute marinade\") would be filtered as metadata. This is a pre-existing issue, not introduced by these changes, but the new `MAIN RECIPE:` addition reinforces that METADATA_PATTERNS is worth auditing for false-positive breadth as it grows.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `^--\\s*\\w` anchor is precise: it requires at least one word character after the dashes, so a line that is literally `\"--\"` (a horizontal rule OCR artifact) would not match, but also would not be a title candidate for other reasons.\n- The `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern is correctly case-insensitive and allows optional whitespace before the colon, which is good OCR resilience.\n- The dedup comment (\"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\") and the guard being opt-in (return true to protect, not to filter) is the right logic shape — it is easy to reason about."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a160bc4896b710273 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 18402\ntool_uses: 9\nduration_ms: 58933</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7a79a908-8d4c-4852-8920-c5c4df3c5fbb","uuid":"0f576deb-f2ec-404f-84da-5a0a1db67df7","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the following changes made to `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. Focus on correctness, consistency, and whether the approach is sound.\n\n**Change 1: METADATA_PATTERNS addition (line ~77)**\n```typescript\n/^MAIN\\s+RECIPE\\s*:/i,    // \"MAIN RECIPE: ...\" structural prefix lines\n```\n\n**Change 2: passesHardFilters() addition (after bullet-list check, line ~322)**\n```typescript\n// Lines starting with \"--\" are sub-section headers (e.g., \"--VARIATION:\", \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA\")\nif (/^--\\s*\\w/.test(text)) return false;\n```\n\n**Change 3: Dedup logic guard (line ~1189)**\n```typescript\nselected = selected.filter((a) => {\n  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n  // Protect compound titles — these use explicit separators and the full form is intentional\n  if (/ [+:] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n  return !selected.some(\n    (b) =>\n      b !== a &&\n      aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) &&\n      b.text.length < a.text.length\n  );\n});\n```\n\n**Context:**\n- This file extracts recipe titles from OCR text\n- METADATA_PATTERNS filters out non-title lines early\n- passesHardFilters() is a hard gate before scoring\n- The dedup logic keeps the SHORTER candidate when one is a substring of another (this is intentional and must not be changed)\n- The compound title guard prevents ` : ` and ` + ` separated titles from being eliminated by the shorter-wins rule\n\nPlease check:\n1. Are the regex patterns correct and not over-broad?\n2. Is the `/ [+:] /` compound guard in the dedup potentially harmful for edge cases?\n3. Are there consistency issues — should the `--` pattern also be added to METADATA_PATTERNS instead of passesHardFilters?\n4. Any other concerns?\n\nRead the relevant sections of the file at `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` for full context (lines 45-80, 306-350, 1184-1200).","agentId":"a160bc4896b710273","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have enough context for a thorough review. Here are my findings:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: title-extractor.ts — Three Changes\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nAll three changes are directionally correct and solve real problems. The `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern and the `--` hard filter are sound. The compound title guard in dedup is the most interesting change — it works for its stated purpose but has two edge cases worth considering. One consistency issue stands out: the `--` pattern should almost certainly also be in `METADATA_PATTERNS`, not only in `passesHardFilters`.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. The `--` filter is placed in the wrong layer and will miss the coalescing path\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:325`\n\nThe `--` check lives only in `passesHardFilters()`. However, `looksLikeMetadata()` is called in three additional places: the coalescing loop at lines 479 and 491, and the merge-block check at line 536. A `--VARIATION:` line sitting between two real title lines could still participate in coalescing because the coalescing guard checks `looksLikeMetadata()`, not `passesHardFilters()`.\n\nThe comment on the pattern says \"sub-section headers\" — that is exactly the same semantic category as `SEZON:`, `KATEGORIA:`, `PORCJI:` which all live in `METADATA_PATTERNS`. Placing `--` in `passesHardFilters` only gives partial protection.\n\n**Recommendation**: Add the pattern to `METADATA_PATTERNS` as well (or instead). It can stay in `passesHardFilters` too — the redundancy is harmless, and a comment like \"also in METADATA_PATTERNS\" makes the intent explicit:\n\n```typescript\n// METADATA_PATTERNS addition:\n/^--\\s*\\w/,    // \"--VARIATION:\", \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA\" sub-section headers\n\n// passesHardFilters can then either remove it (trusting looksLikeMetadata) or keep it with a note.\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 2. The compound guard `/ [+:] /` in dedup can over-protect noise survivors\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1195`\n\nThe guard fires on any title that contains a space-colon-space or space-plus-space. A candidate like `\"Ciasto: 200g mąki 3 jajka\"` contains ` : ` and would be protected from the shorter-wins rule even though it is clearly ingredient spillover. The `:` separator appears in structural section headers too (e.g., `\"MAIN RECIPE: Classic Tart\"`), though that particular case is already filtered earlier.\n\nThe pattern also does not cover ` & ` which line 348 treats as an equivalent multi-title separator — if `\"CIASTO & LODY\"` is a compound title and a shorter substring `\"CIASTO\"` is also a candidate, the guard would not protect it.\n\nThe risk is low in practice because hard filters and scoring should eliminate most noise before this point, but the guard is asymmetric with line 348's separator set (`[+:&/]`). At minimum, the inconsistency is a latent bug.\n\n**Recommendation**: Align the dedup guard with line 348's separator set for internal consistency:\n\n```typescript\nif (/ [+:&] /.test(a.text)) return true;\n```\n\n(Omitting `/` is intentional — slash separators are breadcrumb-style and are filtered at line 321 when count >= 2, and a single-slash compound would be unusual in a dedup context.)\n\n### 3. `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern anchoring is correct but narrower than the real phenomenon\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:77`\n\n`/^MAIN\\s+RECIPE\\s*:/i` is anchored to the start of the string and requires `RECIPE` specifically. The stated motivation is \"structural prefix lines.\" Other structurally similar prefixes — `BASE RECIPE:`, `CLASSIC RECIPE:`, `ORIGINAL RECIPE:` — would not be caught. This is not wrong, but if the pattern was added to handle a real observed case, the comment should name the case. If it was added speculatively, it may not be needed.\n\nThis is not a bug, but if you start seeing `BASE RECIPE: ...` or similar survivors, the pattern will need expansion. Consider whether the existing colon-ending filter at line 330 (`/:\\s*$/.test(text.trim()) && !/ : /.test(text)`) would already catch `MAIN RECIPE: Classic Tart` (it would, since it ends with the value, not a bare colon). If the METADATA_PATTERNS entry is only needed to also suppress these in the coalescing path, that's the relevant distinction to document in the comment.\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n### The `/ [+:] /` test appears in three separate locations with slight variations\n\nLine 330 uses `/ : /`, line 348 uses `/ [+:&/] /`, and line 1195 uses `/ [+:] /`. All three encode the concept \"this is a compound separator, not a structural colon.\" The divergence between these three will become a maintenance problem when a new separator type is introduced. Consider extracting a shared constant or predicate:\n\n```typescript\nconst COMPOUND_SEPARATOR_RE = / [+:&] /;\n```\n\nand referencing it at all three sites.\n\n### The `\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b` and `\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ` patterns in METADATA_PATTERNS have no line-start anchor\n\nThese are intentional (the comment explains OCR-corrupted prefixes). But they also mean a title like `\"STEK Z 30 MIN MARYNATY\"` (\"steak with 30-minute marinade\") would be filtered as metadata. This is a pre-existing issue, not introduced by these changes, but the new `MAIN RECIPE:` addition reinforces that METADATA_PATTERNS is worth auditing for false-positive breadth as it grows.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `^--\\s*\\w` anchor is precise: it requires at least one word character after the dashes, so a line that is literally `\"--\"` (a horizontal rule OCR artifact) would not match, but also would not be a title candidate for other reasons.\n- The `MAIN RECIPE:` pattern is correctly case-insensitive and allows optional whitespace before the colon, which is good OCR resilience.\n- The dedup comment (\"DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC\") and the guard being opt-in (return true to protect, not to filter) is the right logic shape — it is easy to reason about."}],"totalDurationMs":58933,"totalTokens":18402,"totalToolUseCount":9,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1718,"cache_read_input_tokens":14983,"output_tokens":1700,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1718},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
